 moments in photography’s history, gravitating toward the analogue basis of photographic mediums. Their work announces that photography has become—not obsolete—but “late,” opened up by the potentially critical forces of anachronism. Through a strategy of return—of refusing to let go—the work of these artists proposes an afterlife and survival of the photographic in contemporary art, a formal lateness wherein photography finds its way forward through resistance to the contemporary itself.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 7aPhotography / General.2bisacsh  aPhotography, Analogue, Feminism, Late Style, Anachronism, Medium, Zoe Leonard, Tacita Dean, Sharon Lockhart, Moyra Davey.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022z97831107665090 cprintz978022603511640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226821382423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226821382/original  a978-3-11-076650-9  University of Chicago Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles